# Controller Guidelines

## Core Principles
- Controllers are **thin** — receive request, validate, delegate to service, return response
- No business logic in controllers — that belongs in services
- No direct repository or client calls from controllers — always go through services
- All endpoints under `/api/v1/`

## Standard Controller Pattern

```java
@RestController
@RequestMapping("/api/v1/pre-shift-checks")
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class PreShiftCheckController {
    private final PreShiftCheckService preShiftCheckService;

    @PreAuthorize("hasAnyRole('WFM_TEAM_LEVEL_1', 'GP')")
    @PostMapping
    public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<PreShiftCheckResponseDto>> create(
            @Valid @RequestBody CreatePreShiftCheckRequest request) {
        PreShiftCheckResponseDto result = preShiftCheckService.create(request);
        return ResponseEntity
                .status(HttpStatus.CREATED)
                .body(ApiResponse.success(result, "Pre-shift check created"));
    }

    @PreAuthorize("hasRole('WFM_TEAM_LEVEL_1')")
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<PreShiftCheckResponseDto>> getById(@PathVariable Long id) {
        PreShiftCheckResponseDto result = preShiftCheckService.getById(id);
        return ResponseEntity.ok(ApiResponse.success(result));
    }
}
```

## Rules
- Always return `ResponseEntity<ApiResponse<T>>` for success responses
- Use `@PreAuthorize` on every protected endpoint — never forget role checks
- If all endpoints in a controller share the same role set, use `@PreAuthorize` at **class level** — avoid repeating on every method
- Use `@Valid` on `@RequestBody` parameters — without it, Bean Validation is silently ignored
- Use `@Valid` on **nested DTO fields** to cascade validation — without it, validation stops at the first level
- HTTP status codes: `200 OK` for reads/updates, `201 CREATED` for creation, `204 NO_CONTENT` for deletes
- Use `@PathVariable` for resource identifiers, `@RequestParam` for filters
- Use `@RequestHeader(required = false)` for optional headers — no custom resolvers

## Validation Annotations
- Every `@NotNull`, `@NotBlank`, `@Size`, `@Min`, `@Max`, etc. **must** have a `message` attribute — Spring defaults like `"must not be blank"` are not user-friendly
- Use annotation-based validation (`jakarta.validation.constraints`) — not manual `if` checks in controllers

```java
// ✅ Correct — every annotation has a message
@NotNull(message = "Pre-check ID is required")
private Long preCheckId;

@NotBlank(message = "Employee ID is required")
private String employeeId;

// ✅ Correct — @Valid cascades validation into nested DTO
@Valid
@NotNull(message = "Address is required")
private AddressDto address;

// ❌ Wrong — no message, Spring shows "must not be blank"
@NotBlank
private String employeeId;
```

## Security on Endpoints
- Use `@PreAuthorize` (Spring Security) — do NOT create custom `@AuthorizedRoles` annotations
- Roles must be set as `GrantedAuthority` in `Authentication` object
- Enable via `@EnableMethodSecurity` on security config class
